    <h2 style="color: var(--accent-color); margin-bottom: 1.5rem; text-align: center;">Understanding Puppy Growth</h2>

    <div class="edu-card">
      <h3>Growth Rates by Breed Size</h3>
      <p>Not all dogs grow at the same rate. Toy and small breeds often reach their adult weight by 9-12 months. Medium breeds take around 12-14 months, while large and giant breeds continue growing and filling out until they are 18-24 months old. This means a 6-month-old Great Dane has much more growing left to do than a 6-month-old Chihuahua.</p>
    </div>

    <div class="edu-card">
      <h3>The "Multiplier" Methods</h3>
      <p>A common rule of thumb for medium to large breeds is to take their weight at 16 weeks (4 months) and multiply it by two to get their estimated adult weight. For toy and small breeds, multiplying their 6-week weight by four often provides a reasonable estimate. Our calculator uses more sophisticated growth curves based on specific size categories.</p>
    </div>

    <div class="edu-card">
      <h3>Factors Affecting Growth</h3>
      <p>While genetics play the largest role, a puppy's growth can also be influenced by their nutrition, overall health, and whether/when they were spayed or neutered. Overfeeding a puppy won't make them a larger adult; it will only make them an overweight puppy and can lead to joint problems, especially in large breeds.</p>
