  <div class="faq-container">
    <h2 style="color: var(--accent-color); margin-bottom: 1.5rem; text-align: center;">Frequently Asked Questions</h2>

    <div class="faq-item">
      <div class="faq-question">How accurate is a puppy weight calculator?</div>
      <div class="faq-answer">A puppy weight calculator provides a good estimate based on standard growth curves, but genetics, nutrition, and health all play a role. It is usually within 10-20% of the final adult weight for most mixed and purebred dogs.</div>
    </div>

    <div class="faq-item">
      <div class="faq-question">When do dogs stop growing?</div>
      <div class="faq-answer">Toy and small breeds usually stop growing around 9-12 months. Medium breeds stop around 12-14 months, while large and giant breeds can take anywhere from 18 to 24 months to reach their full adult size and weight.</div>
    </div>

    <div class="faq-item">
      <div class="faq-question">Can you tell how big a puppy will get by their paws?</div>
      <div class="faq-answer">While large paws can sometimes indicate a larger adult dog, it is not a foolproof method. Growth rates vary greatly, and paw size alone cannot definitively predict adult weight as accurately as tracking weight over time on a growth chart.</div>
    </div>

    <div class="faq-item">
      <div class="faq-question">How can I estimate my mixed breed puppy's adult weight?</div>
      <div class="faq-answer">For mixed breeds, you can use a general growth curve calculator based on their current age and weight. Select the estimated adult size category (small, medium, large) if known, or use a general multiplier based on their weight at 16 weeks (multiply by 2).</div>
    </div>

    <div class="faq-item">
      <div class="faq-question">Does spaying or neutering affect my puppy's final weight?</div>
      <div class="faq-answer">Early spaying or neutering can sometimes cause a dog to grow slightly taller and potentially heavier because it delays the closure of the bone growth plates. However, the overall difference in adult weight is usually minimal.</div>
    </div>
  </div>

